The Ethel and James Flinn Foundation traces its roots three generations back to Elisha Flinn.  He was born in 1843 and lived in New York State until coming to Detroit in 1865 to enter the practice of law.  Elisha Flinns clients were companies involved in natural resources but he gradually discontinued the practice of law to enter the business of buying and selling pine timber in Michigan.  He formed a partnership with his former partner under the name of Robinson and Flinn and when the Michigan pine timber gave out they moved their activities to other states and later to Minnesota.  Robinson and Flinn associated with others from Michigan and purchased considerable acreage of pine land in Minnesota.  In 1892 iron ore was found on their Minnesota properties and from that time until his death in 1911 Elisha Flinns principal business was iron ore mining in and around Eveleth, Minnesota.  He was president of the Lake Superior Iron and Chemical Company, a vice president of old Detroit National Bank and a director of the Wayne County Savings Bank and the Detroit Trust Company.  In 1871 he married Samantha Whitwood.  Elisha and Samantha lived on Putnam Ave. in Detroit and raised two children James H. and Mary W.

Elisha Flinns son, James H. Flinn, was born in 1874.  He graduated from the University of Michigan Law School.  James Flinn devoted most of his business career to managing and supervising the iron ore activities in Minnesota.  By 1899 the town of Eveleth and Elisha Flinn and his associates had a dilemma as iron ore had been discovered under the original town of Eveleth.  To mine this valuable iron ore supply it would be necessary to move the towns business district five blocks east.  James Flinn temporarily relocated to Eveleth to supervise the move.  He was responsible for installation of steam hoists which pulled the buildings up the towns main street.  Soon one-hundred buildings were moved safely onto the new main street allowing Flinn and his associates to profit from the previously unobtainable ore.

James Flinn married Ethel Garretson in 1906.  Ethel and James raised three children, George, Ethel W. and James H. Jr. first on Seminole in Detroit and then in Grosse Pointe, Michigan.  It was Ethel and James who set the course for the Ethel and James Flinn Foundation.  They established a number of living and testamentary trusts that provided for distribution of the trust remainders upon termination to a philanthropic organization that would provide for the support of research into the causes and/or research into the treatment of nervous and mental diseases.

Ethel W. Peggy Flinn with her cousin and her lawyer established the Foundation in 1976.  Her intent was to remember her parents, Ethel and James and her brother, James H., Jr. and to consolidate and direct the familys philanthropy toward the purposes already expressed by her parents in their trusts documents; research into the causes and/or research into the treatment of nervous and mental diseases.  Peggy graduated from Columbia Presbyterian College of Nursing in New York as a registered nurse and was a volunteer nurse with the Red Cross during World War II.  She was particularly interested in children and was a longtime and life member of the Board of Trustees of Childrens Hospital of Michigan.  Her life passion was horses.  She owned, rode and showed champion horses throughout the country.  She was a life member of the American Horseshow Association.  She provided initial funding to the foundation during her lifetime and left an endowment to the foundation on her death in 1994.

Jim Flinn, Jr. attended Princeton and Babson University.  He was afflicted with schizophrenia in his early 20s and following the death of his father in 1952 resided for the rest of his adult life at the St. Joseph Mercy Health System in Ann Arbor, Michigan.  The caregivers at St. Joseph Mercy Hospital provided a unique, close, caring and supportive environment that contributed to Jims long life and to his good quality of life.  Jims interests were many and varied; reading, history, University of Michigan football, movies, gardening, bike riding and traveling.  Helping the disadvantaged and philanthropy were of special interest to him.  In later years he made substantial contributions to the foundation and to charities generally.  Upon Jims death all of the Flinns interests were transferred to the foundation leaving as a legacy a philanthropic foundation that will improve the lives of those with mental illness.

Manic systems decreased since last appointment.  Patient seems to be responding to aripiprazole.  Will consider starting lithium for long term maintenance.

Have started the patient on fluoxetine 20mg/day and olanzapine 5mg/day because the patient is reported to have responded to these medications in the past.  Patient is currently very depressed.  Will see her again in one week.

There is little change in the patient's symptoms.  She remains quite depressed, but not have any active suicidal ideation or intent, even though she sometimes wishes she was dead.  No evidence of psychotic thought processes or content.  I have increased the dose of fluoxetine to 40mg/day.  Will see her again in a week.  Told the patient to call me if she begins to feel worse or has any increased thoughts of wanting to hurt herself.

John S. is a 20-year-old man who was brought to the outpatient clinic by his mother. During the intake interview by the psychiatric social worker John's mother reported that her son had become increasingly irritable and confused during the last few weeks. At times it seemed like he was talking to himself. Often he would make strange comments that didn't make any sense to her or her husband.

        John's mother described her son as a solitary child when he was young with few friends. He was a slightly below-average student during most of his years in school. In his teen years his school performance began to deteriorate. By the time he graduated he was barely passing his courses. His major interest at that time was to go out to a bar with a small group of acquaintances and drink beer in the evenings. When he finished school his parents insisted that he get a job. After several weeks of searching he found a job at a local fast food restaurant. At first he was put to work serving customers at the counter. It was about this time that John's mother noticed that her son was developing some peculiar habits. He often seems to be talking to himself. He paid less attention to his dress and grooming, often not taking a shower for a week at a time. She sometimes heard him walking around the house in the middle of the night. One morning she came down to the kitchen and found John lining the inside of his baseball cap with aluminum foil. When she asked him what he was doing he got angry and stormed out of the house.  Since that morning he has become more irritable and argumentative in general.
        Problems have also appeared at work around the same time. John's coworkers and the customers became increasingly uncomfortable with him. After some complaints, the manager transferred him to the kitchen where he could help with the cooking and cleaning. About 3 weeks ago John got into a violent argument with the manager of the restaurant and was fired. Since that time has been sitting in the house watching television all day long.

The clinician who saw John during the intake interview described him as guarded and somewhat suspicious.  He seemed preoccupied and periodically looked around the room with some anxiety.  The interviewer thought he may have been responding to internal cues.  During the meeting John made very few spontaneous comments and answered direct questions with monosyllable responses.  When the interviewer asked if he was hearing voices, John stared at her briefly, but did not answer the question.

John S. is a 20-year-old man who was brought to the outpatient clinic by his mother. During the intake interview by the psychiatric social worker John's mother reported that her son had become increasingly irritable and confused during the last few weeks. At times it seemed like he was talking to himself. Often he would make strange comments that didn't make any sense to her or her husband. 

John's mother described her son as a solitary child when he was young with few friends. He was a slightly below-average student during most of his years in school. In his teen years his school performance began to deteriorate. By the time he graduated he was barely passing his courses. His major interest at that time was to go out to a bar with a small group of acquaintances and drink beer in the evenings. When he finished school his parents insisted that he get a job. After several weeks of searching he found a job at a local fast food restaurant. At first he was put to work serving customers at the counter. It was about this time that John's mother noticed that her son was developing some peculiar habits. He often seems to be talking to himself. He paid less attention to his dress and grooming, often not taking a shower for a week at a time. She sometimes heard him walking around the house in the middle of the night. One morning she came down to the kitchen and found John lining the inside of his baseball cap with aluminum foil. When she asked him what he was doing he got angry and stormed out of the house.  Since that morning he has become more irritable and argumentative in general. 
Problems have also appeared at work around the same time. John's coworkers and the customers became increasingly uncomfortable with him. After some complaints, the manager transferred him to the kitchen where he could help with the cooking and cleaning. About 3 weeks ago John got into a violent argument with the manager of the restaurant and was fired. Since that time has been sitting in the house watching television all day long.

The clinician who saw John during the intake interview described him as guarded and somewhat suspicious.  He seemed preoccupied and periodically looked around the room with some anxiety.  The interviewer thought he may have been responding to internal cues.  During the meeting John made very few spontaneous comments and answered direct questions with monosyllable responses.  When the interviewer asked if he was hearing voices, John stared at her briefly, but did not answer the question.

John S. is a 20-year-old man who was brought to the outpatient clinic by his mother. During the intake interview she reported that her son had become increasingly irritable and confused during the last few weeks. At times it seemed like he was talking to himself.
    John’s mother reported that her son had graduated from high school with average grades about a year ago.  He started at the local junior college the following fall, but quit after a month complaining that his teachers did not know what they were talking about.  He spent the next two months lying on the couch in his parents living room watching television.  His parents finally insisted that he look for a job.  After several weeks of searching he found a job at a local fast food restaurant. At first he was put to work waiting on customers at the counter. It was about this time that John's mother noticed that her son was developing some peculiar habits. He often seemed to be talking to himself. He paid less attention to his dress and grooming than he had before, often not taking a shower for a week at a time. His mother  assumed that he was having trouble sleeping because she often heard him walking around the house in the middle of the night.  One morning she came down to the kitchen and found John lining the inside of his baseball cap with aluminum foil. When she asked him what he was doing he got angry and stormed out of the house.  Since that morning he has become more irritable and argumentative.
    John began to have problems at work around the same time.  His coworkers and the customers became increasingly uncomfortable with his unusual behavior and poor hygiene. After some complaints, the manager transferred him to the kitchen to help with the cooking and cleaning. About 3 weeks ago John got into a violent argument with the manager of the restaurant and was fired. Since that time he has rarely left his parent’s home.  His mother finally persuaded him to come to the clinic to seek help.   
    John’s mother described her son’s early years as more or less normal.  He began talking and walking at the appropriate ages.  He seemed reasonably happy playing with his toys and interacting with other members of the family, including his older sister and brother.  During his early years in school he was described by teachers as a “quiet child” who got along with the other children, but had few real friends.  In high school he never dated and attended few social functions.  He was an average student until his last two years in high school when his grades began to deteriorate. By the time he graduated he was barely passing his courses.
    The clinician who saw John during the intake interview described him as guarded and somewhat suspicious.  He seemed preoccupied and periodically looked around the room with some anxiety.  The interviewer thought he may have been responding to internal cues.  During the meeting John made very few spontaneous comments, but was willing to answer direct questions. When the interviewer asked if he was hearing voices, John nodded.  When asked what they said, he replied that they talk about his thoughts.  When asked why he put the aluminum foil in his baseball cap, John answered, “to stop the thoughts from coming in.”  John denied using drugs or excessive alcohol.
    The intake clinician who interviewed John made a preliminary DSM diagnosis of schizophrenia, paranoid type. He administered the Brief Negative Symptom Assessment (BNSA) and Positive Symptom Rating Scale (PSRS) for schizophrenia, and the Global Rating Scales and referred John to another clinician in the clinic for treatment.

<h1>Intake Clinical Note</h1><br/>
Steve B. is a 34 year old married, insurance salesman.  He was accompanied to the outpatient clinic by his wife. She sat quietly while he paced around the room and explained that he was feeling great and didn't think he needed to see anyone. 
    Steve explained that he had been depressed a few weeks ago, but now felt much better. He immediately went on to tell the social worker about some of the unique business plans he was developing,  including one for a online custom bakery. He was convinced that this would revolutionize the baking industry.  "I have a special talent for business innovations like this.", he added.  "Everyone I talk to agrees with me.  They haven't seen anything like it before."  The social worker reported that it was difficult to interrupt the rapid flow of Steve's speech.  After several tries she was finally able to ask him about some of the details of his business plan, such as how the customers would get the baked goods. Steve responded by becoming increasingly irritated. "You're just a skeptic like my wife," he yelled. " I can't tell you any of the details because there are people around who will try to steal them."  Steve talked rapidly during the interview, jumping from one topic to another, often with no apparent logical connections between the topics. As he spoke he paced around the room, periodically sitting in the chair next to his wife, and then jumping up to pace some more.
    After a few minutes, Steve's wife gently asked her husband to sit down so she could talk to the social worker.  He appeared irritated at her request, but finally sat down. She reported that the couple had been married for 6 years.  During that time Steve had had periodic changes in his mood.  Sometimes he would be depressed for several weeks and then he would snap out of it and seem normal for a while.  During one of these episodes Steve's primary care provider prescribed some antidepressant medication for him, but Steve stopped taking the medication after a few weeks when his depression ended. This time, when the depression ended, he had a brief period of normal mood and then became more and more excited about some of his business plans.  He kept saying that everything was going to be great now.  He had a great deal of energy and rarely slept more than 2 or 3 hours a night.  She reported that Steve talked incessantly about his brilliant new ideas and how they would make him a fortune.  He withdrew a significant amount of money from their savings to invest in the projects.  The money disappeared and she has no idea where it went.  When she asked Steve about the money he began yelling at her and accused her of doubting him.
    She thought that he would settle down in a few days, but, instead, his thinking became more and more optimistic and unrealistic.  He was convinced that they would soon be rich from his Internet businesses.  Sometimes she could not understand what he was talking about.  Finally, she convinced him to come to the outpatient clinic by telling him that one of the doctors from the clinic had called to inquire about one of Steve's projects and wanted to meet him. 
    The social worker who interviewed Steve made a preliminary DSM diagnosis of bipolar disorder, manic.  She administered the Brief Bipolar Disorder Symptom Scale (BDSS) and the Global Rating Scales and referred Steve to another clinician in the office for treatment.

DP has completed her 7th ECT, 1 week after completeing an inpatient course of 6 ECT, three times weekly.  There is distinct overall improvement in her appearance and mood, although she does remain symptomatic. She is no longer expereincing auditory hallucinations of a self-deprecating kind. She is medication free at this point, except she is seeking assistance with severe I and M insomnia.  There is some degree of confusion, but much improved over previous course of ECT (biltaeral).  Migraine headaches are more frequent since start of ECT, and she believes the discontinuation of low-dose Depakote accounts for this. Decisions about frequency and duration of ECT will be needed soon, as well as choice of maintenance phase pharmacotherapy in light of numerous previous drug failures.

DP has completed a single additional ECT since last seen, now on a weekly basis.  With the exception of headache on the day of ECT, she is having less p[roblem with migraines since spacing the treatments out.  There is minimal ECT-indiced confusion except on the days of treatment. Addition of olanzepine 5 mg has assisted somewhat with insomnia, but there is still significant I and M insomnia on some nghts.  Low energy remains a major concern; otherwise mood seems to be better than last week. No apparent fiddiculty tolerating resumption of Cymbalta, although this is at lower dose than she previously was maintained on.   No current plan to initiate lithium since she is undergoing course of ECT.

Weekly ECT continus; no significant confusion and headaches are manageable.  However, clinical course has largely leveled off at this point.  At 10mg Zyprexa at HS, sleep has improved somewhat, although not completely.  Cymbalata now at 120mg daily.  Energy remains low, and there is a hint of daytime sedation, perhaps due to the Zyprexa (senstive to antipsychotics in the past).  Lithium still being held due to ongoing ECT.

Met with Steve and Med clinic staff (Vicki)  as a follow up after his appt with Dr. Bedi. Steve is a step down from Interact ACT services to med clinic due to Steve refusing Interact services at this time.


 


 Met with Steve initially with med clinic staff and then alone. Steve was seen by Dr. Tatini on 2/15/13 and referred to Doctordue to Steve's Hx and request for Suboxone medications.


 


He met with Doctortoday and was prescribed Zyprexa and Lexapro.


 


Per med clinic staff, before this worker joined the contact, Steve was making statements about his how he felt the desire to harm others when he was not getting his needs met. Again, per med clinic staff, his language was graphic , but did not disclose a plan or any targets. Steve went into great detail about how he feels in "miserable" pain without his pain medication.


 


He has a long HX of SA issues with his drugs of choice being opioid. Steve was able to verbal he has addiction issues stating," anyone who takes pain medication that long is going to be addicted like me." Although he made statements about his addiction, he denied any withdrawal symptoms.


 


Med clinic staff have tried to find a primary care doctor that will accept Steves insurance and provide pain management needs. Since 2/15/13, the Family Health Center, KCMS/ WMED, Dr. Harrell's (previous PCP) and Meridian Medicaid  insurance have been notified. All have declined to accept Steve back in their practice due to Steve's past behavior of verbal threats and physical outbursts mostly when he perceived his pain needs were not being met. Medicaid Meridian is assisting KCMHSAS med clinic staff in locating a provider to accept Steve for PCP services.


 


Steve has a long HX of receiving MH services including , but not limited to multiple KPH stays, ACT services and case management. He also has an extensive criminal HX involving violent crimes.


 


Since Steve reported a vague desire to harm others, EMH staff was called for assistance. AT that point Steve recanted any HI, SI or SIB and reported he would not "harm no one unless I get put back in the hospital then I will hurt someone, they ain't locking me up in KPH to die." EMH staff provided support , but since Steve was not suicidal, homicidal or presenting with MH symptoms that could benefit from an inpatient stay nor did not want this level of care, EMH staff did not screen Steve.


 


Steve went on to state that he strongly believes he is dying from liver failure or cancer and discussed how he euthanized his cousin that was dying from liver failure last year. He reported "shooting up as much morphine as I could in him cause his heart would not stop." Steve stated that he would like someone to help him out in that way "when my time comes, which could be soon." It repeatedly stated to this worker he was not suicidal but felt he may need to "do whatever " is needed to assist in euthanasia for himself from medical issues "not mental health issues." Steve denied any plans or desire to "do any euthansiana now." Steve declined any ER medical intervention stating," they wont help me , they will tell me to go to a primary care doctor."


 


Med clinic staff contacted Bridgeways, upon Steve's and Dr. Bedi's request , and was informed that Steves prior case manager does not have any openings. Steve reported he would only receive services from a particular case manager at


 


Services ACT staff were contacted by med clinic staff (and a message was left to link Steve with services.


 


Although Steve had made multiple statements about violent behaviors towards others, he denied any intention or plans to harm others and stated, " that is if they try to put me in the hospital to make me die there then will hurt one of those staff at KPH and watch them bleed."


 


This worker assisted him with his goal of gaining access to methadone. Steve has a HX of being barred from the Victory clinic due to threatening and aggressive behaviors. Access staff () contacted the Victory and left a message requesting the Victory clinic consider him for services. Steve signed a  release fro the Victory Clinic.  Steve disclosed he using marijuana weekly when he can smoke and "not choke on it  and Vicodin between "3- 12  tablets a day."


Steve was future oriented discussing his desire to "get back on Methadone or Suboxone, that's why I came here in the first place."


 


Steve was cooperative and requested this worker assist him in having his medication delivered. He ended the contact stating he has to go home and rest since he "don't have no more Vicodin for pain."


 


Plan continues to be to call Steve with the outcome of requesting Victory and Senior Services ACT. No other concerns mentioned.
